{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"So there are 26 letters in the alphabet and 10 numbers (0-9) which give us 36 keys on the typewriter. Now the probability of typing the alphabet (with 26 digits) out in order (per try) is "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\frac {1}{36^{26}}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Now we multiply this numerator by "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"1,000^7"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" to work out the chances of all of them typing it out in any one given second, which takes us to "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\frac {1,000^7}{36^{26}}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". That seems like a lot of seconds, so we convert it to years, so it looks like this: ("},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"36^{26}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":") ÷ ("},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"1,000^7"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":") ÷ ("},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"60 \times 60 \times 24 \times 365.25"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":") and we type the answer in a calculator (or more like google nowadays) and we get around 922 billion. It seems like a long time to type the alphabet correctly."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}
